inimal maintenance)\tHigh (replacement every 2-3 years) Skill Level Required\tModerate (following proper steps)\tEasy application, poor long-term results Under-Sink Performance\t⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Seals plywood edges from water damage\t⭐ FAIL - water penetration causes immediate peeling Resale Value Impact\t+$500-1000 (professional finish)\t-$200 (cheap appearance, visible wear) VERDICT: Paint wins decisively for bathroom applications. Peel-and-stick veneer is categorically unsuitable for high-humidity environments. THE WINNING SOLUTION: WATERBORNE ALKYD PAINT SYSTEM Why This Method Works for Plywood Cabinets: Your cabinet construction (plywood with possible laminate facing) requires a system that: ✅ Seals moisture at vulnerable plywood edges (especially under-sink area) ✅ Bonds to mixed surfaces (plywood, laminate, existing finish) ✅ Withstands humidity from showers and steam ✅ Provides durable, wipeable surface for daily cleaning ✅ Delivers furniture-quality finish that looks professional, not DIY RECOMMENDED PAINT SYSTEM (2026 INDUSTRY STANDARD) Option A: Premium Choice (Best Results) Benjamin Moore ADVANCE Interior Paint System Primer: STIX Waterborne Bonding Primer Topcoat: ADVANCE Waterborne Alkyd Paint (Semi-Gloss or Satin) Color: Custom matched to your pink preference Cost: $180-220 total Performance: 15+ year lifespan, superior moisture resistance Option B: Budget-Friendly (Still Professional) Sherwin-Williams Cabinet Paint System Primer: Multi-Purpose Water-Based Primer Topcoat: Emerald Urethane Trim Enamel (Semi-Gloss) Cost: $140-180 total Performance: 10-12 year lifespan, excellent moisture resistance Option C: DIY-Friendly System Rust-Oleum Cabinet Transformations Kit Complete system with deglosser, bond coat, and topcoat Cost: $120-150 Performance: 7-10 years, simplified application MY RECOMMENDATION: Go with Option A (Benjamin Moore ADVANCE) if you want once-and-done quality. The upfront cost difference ($40-60) is negligible compared to the durability advantage. 